{"topics":[{"topicLabel":"Planning, expecting and arranging","topicThesaurusName":"topics","topicUrl":"http://dictionary.cambridge.org/topics/thinking-about-the-future/planning-expecting-and-arranging/","topicId":"planning-expecting-and-arranging","topicParentId":"thinking-about-the-future"}],"dictionaryCode":"american-english","entryContent":"<di><header><title>watch<\/title><\/header> <pos-block><header><info><posgram><pos>noun<\/pos><\/posgram> <audio type=\"pronunciation\" region=\"us\"><source type=\"audio/mpeg\" src=\"https://dictionary.cambridge.org/media/american-english/us_pron/w/wat/watch/watch.mp3\"/><source type=\"audio/ogg\" src=\"https://dictionary.cambridge.org/media/american-english/us_pron_ogg/w/wat/watch/watch.ogg\"/><\/audio> <pron>/<ipa>wɑtʃ<\/ipa>, <ipa>wɔtʃ<\/ipa>/<\/pron> <\/info><\/header><sense-block><header><title>SMALL CLOCK<\/title><\/header> <def-block><definition><info><lvl>\u203a<\/lvl> <gram>[<gcs><gc>C<\/gc><\/gcs>]<\/gram><\/info> <def>a small clock usually worn on a strap around the wrist, or sometimes carried in a pocket: <\/def><\/definition><examp><eg>She looked at her watch and said, \"It\u2019s a quarter to five.\"<\/eg><\/examp><\/def-block><\/sense-block> <sense-block><header><title>LOOKING AT<\/title><\/header> <def-block><definition><info><lvl>\u203a<\/lvl> <gram>[<gcs><gc>C/U<\/gc><\/gcs>]<\/gram><\/info> <def>an act of guarding someone or something to make sure the person or property stays safe and in the right place: <\/def><\/definition><examp><info><gram>[<gcs><gc>U<\/gc><\/gcs>]<\/gram><\/info><eg>The prison guards kept a close watch on him.<\/eg><\/examp><\/def-block> <def-block><definition><info><lvl>\u203a<\/lvl> <gram>[<gcs><gc>C/U<\/gc><\/gcs>]<\/gram><\/info> <def>Watch is also a period during which someone is responsible for guarding or looking around to be sure that property or people are safe, or the person who is responsible: <\/def><\/definition><examp><info><gram>[<gcs><gc>C<\/gc><\/gcs>]<\/gram><\/info><